Summary: This section introduces decals as a method for adding texture detail to 3D scenes, particularly for organic elements, breaking up repetition, and adding variations like footprints or puddles.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_decals.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_decals.rst
Summary: This section explains how decals can be used for dynamic gameplay elements like bullet impacts and scorches, and how they can be managed for performance.

Decals can represent temporary or persistent gameplay effects such as bullet impacts and explosion scorches. Using an AnimationPlayer node or a script, decals can be made to fade over time (and then be removed using queue_free()) to improve performance.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using Decals
Path: godot/tutorials/3d/using_decals.rst
Summary: This section explains the concept and use cases of blob shadows in Godot, particularly for mobile development and enhancing depth perception.
Blob shadows are often used in mobile projects or for retro art styles because real-time lighting can be too demanding for low-end mobile devices. When using baked lightmaps with fully baked lights, dynamic objects do not cast shadows from these lights, making them appear flat and disconnected from the scene, almost as if floating. Blob shadows provide an approximate shadow for dynamic objects, improving depth perception and serving as a gameplay element, such as indicating landing spots in 3D platformers. They can also function as a form of ambient occlusion in real-time lighting scenarios where Screen Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO) is too expensive or unstable, like representing shadows under vehicles.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using Decals
